<!DOCTYPE html>
                <html>
                <head>
                    <title>On the Doctoral Thesis of David Hilbert</title>
                <?php include_once 'Elemental/header.php'; ?><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><br><br><h5> This article is reformatted from originally published at <a href="https://www.cantorsparadise.com/on-the-doctoral-thesis-of-david-hilbert-978708766389"><strong>TDS(Towards Data Science)</strong></a></h5></br><h5> <a href="https://areebamerriam.medium.com/?source=post_page-----978708766389--------------------------------">Author : Areeba Merriam</a> </h5></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content4 cid-tt5SM2WLsM" id="content4-2" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="row justify-content-center">
                    <div class="title col-md-12 col-lg-9">
                        <h3 class="mbr-section-title mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-2">
                            <strong>On the Doctoral Thesis of David Hilbert</h3></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5 text-muted">“The infinite! No other question has ever moved so profoundly the spirit of man”</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*ahy12g2hFP21x7YolyQ_Ug.jpeg"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">“Is mathematics doomed to suffer the same fate as other sciences that have split into separate branches?… Mathematics is, in my opinion, an indivisible whole…”— David Hilbert</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><span>D</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Hilbert" target="_self">avid Hilbert</a> (1862–1943) was a German mathematician who possessed such diversified knowledge that spanned so many branches of mathematics. Such as, the idea of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_space" target="_self">Hilbert spaces</a> was presented by him in the subject of analysis. In the area of approximation theory, he introduced the idea of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_matrix" target="_self">Hilbert matrix</a>. He further advanced the fields of radiation physics, the kinetic theory of gases, and the general theory of relativity. He also contributed to algebraic number theory, algebraic invariants, commutative algebra, and calculus of variations. He, undoubtedly, left a long-standing impact on advancements in the subject.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The theorems he proved include <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_basis_theorem" target="_self">Hilbert’s Basis Theorem</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_Nullstellensatz" target="_self">Hilbert’s Nullstellensatz</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_Theorem_90" target="_self">Hilbert’s Satz 90</a><em> </em>(or theorem 90), and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_irreducibility_theorem" target="_self">Hilbert’s irreducibility theorem</a>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Indeed, he is one of the most influential scientists of the 19th and early 20th centuries who inspired many great mathematicians to come.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Early Life</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">He started his university education at Königsberg where he got a chance to study under <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heinrich_Friedrich_Weber" target="_self">Heinrich Friedrich Weber</a> (1843–1912) who was the only full professor of mathematics there. Also, he established a life-long friendship with a guy named <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Minkowski" target="_self">Herman Minkowski</a> (1864–1909) who with his precocious abilities won a prestigious award from the Paris Academy at the young age of 17. Their friendship strongly influenced each other's work in the coming years.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Hilbert completed his doctorate in the year 1885, under the supervision of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferdinand_von_Lindemann" target="_self">Ferdinand Von Lindemann</a> (1852–1939), with his dissertation entitled <em>Über invariante Eigenschaften spezieller binärer Formen, insbesondere der Kugelfunktionen</em> (“<strong>On the invariant properties of special binary forms, in particular, the spherical harmonic functions</strong>”).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">He served at the same University for ten years as a Privatdozent. Then <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Felix_Klein" target="_self">Felix Klein</a> (1849–1925) insisted and helped him to join the University of Göttingen as a professor of mathematics. Göttingen became a flourishing institute afterward.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-10">
            <br>
                <hr class="hr5">
            <br>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">PhD Thesis</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">While deciding the possible areas to work on for the doctoral work, he thought of investigating the generalization of continued fractions. He discussed that with his advisor Lindemann. Lindemann informed him that <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Gustav_Jacob_Jacobi" target="_self">Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi</a> (1804–1851) has already successfully come up with such a generalization. Instead, Lindemann suggested he should consider a problem in a somewhat modern subject i.e <strong>the theory of algebraic invariants</strong>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The theory of algebraic invariants has its deep roots in analytical geometry given by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" target="_self">René Descartes</a> (1596–1650) in the seventeenth century. Such as the notion that horizontal and vertical coordinates are real numbers that are represented by x and y, respectively. And geometric figures can be obtained from algebraic equations and in return algebraic equations can be mapped to geometric figures too.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We know that the size and shape of figures remain the same upon any change in their orientation with respect to the axes. Hence, some properties of their associated algebraic forms remain invariant. These invariants then help to characterize the geometric figures.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">That’s how the development of the theory of invariants of algebraic forms under several transformation groups happened. Due to more rigorous results, the algebraic technique surpassed the geometric one and soon it became the center of interest for many accomplished mathematicians.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Lindemann suggested uncovering the problem of invariant properties of certain algebraic forms for his PhD thesis. That was certainly a challenging problem for any PhD candidate, except Hilbert. He tackled that problem differently and originally rather than a mundane path that was taken by people in those times.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">He used to say: “<em>… he who seeks for methods without having a definite problem in mind seeks for the most part in vain</em>.” In the end, Lindemann was quite convinced of his significant and robust results.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Minkowski passed the following remarks upon receiving a copy of Hilbert’s dissertation:-</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">“I studied your work with great interest and rejoiced over all the processes which the poor invariants had to pass through before they manage to disappear. I would not have supposed that such a good mathematical theorem could have been obtained in Königsberg.”</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Hilbert was awarded the degree of Doctor of Philosophy when passed his public defense in 1885 in which he had to present two dissertations of his choice.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">One of the propositions which he chose to defend was related to the method of determining absolute electromagnetic resistance, experimentally. The other one was concerned with philosophy.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The Dean of the department administered the following oath:-</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">“I ask you solemnly whether by the given oath you undertake to promise and confirm most conscientiously that you will defend in a manly way true science, extend and embellish it, not for gain’s sake or for attaining a vain shine of glory, but in order that the light of God’s truth shine bright and expand.”</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-10">
            <br>
                <hr class="hr5">
            <br>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">After completing his doctorate Hilbert was suggested to take a tour of Europe to see other great mathematicians. He met Felix Klein in Leipzig, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Poincar%C3%A9" target="_self">Henri Poincaré</a> (1854-1912) in Paris, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leopold_Kronecker" target="_self">Leopold Kronecker</a> (1823–1891) in Berlin. He found Kronecker to be very disagreeable and inflexible to accept new and creative ideas.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">He then returned to Königsberg and become an unpaid lecturer (privatdozent), after passing a public exam. He was all dependent upon a small amount of money paid directly by pupils who used to attend his lectures. In 1892, he became an assistant professor, taking the place of his friend and professor <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adolf_Hurwitz" target="_self">Adolf Hurwitz</a> (1859–1919).</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A few years later, he was offered a place as a full professor at Göttingen. He then moved to Göttingen with his wife and child and stayed there for the rest of his life.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-10">
            <br>
                <hr class="hr5">
            <br>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">His work on the theory of algebraic invariants made him prove the famous <strong>Finiteness Theorem</strong>, in 1888. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Gordan" target="_self">Paul Gordan</a> (1837–1912) attempted to prove the same theorem for binary systems with some computational techniques. Generalizing the theorem for more than two variables was not achieved at that time due to cumbersome calculations.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Hilbert arrived at the proof in a rather different way and demonstrated Hilbert’s basis theorem which showed that <mark>for the invariants of quantics with a different number of variables, there exists a finite set of generators (in an abstract way)</mark>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Hilbert submitted his results to the journal <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematische_Annalen" target="_self">Mathematische Annalen</a>. But, Gordan who considered himself the best expert on the subject “the king of invariants” could not recognize the robustness of Hilbert’s masterpiece and rejected his submission with his remarks that “<em>This is not Mathematics. This is Theology.</em>”</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Besides, Felix Klein was able to appreciate this novel work and mentioned that the work is publishable without a doubt. Moreover, he encouraged Hilbert to further extend this approach in a more general way and submit it again. After receiving the second submission Klein wrote to him,</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">“Without doubt, this is the most important work on general algebra that the Annalen has ever published.”</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">When the usefulness of Hilbert’s approach became inarguably appreciated worldwide, Gordan said “<strong>I have convinced myself that even theology has its merits</strong><em>.</em>”</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">“The art of doing mathematics consists in finding that special case which contains all the germs of generality.”― David Hilbert</p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
