</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Retirement and Death</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Hilbert was forced to retire from his professorship in 1930 when Adolf Hitler became the chancellor of Germany. He executed the law to forbid full-blooded Jews from all teaching positions. Many renowned mathematicians including Courant, Noether, Landau, Bernays, Born, and Franck suffered through this ban.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The minister of education, at one moment, <a href="http://abyss.uoregon.edu/~js/glossary/hilbert.html" target="_self">asked</a> Hilbert “<em>And how is mathematics in Göttingen now that it has been freed of the Jewish influence</em>?” Hilbert said, “<strong>Mathematics in Göttingen? There is really none anymore</strong>.” He died in 1943 at the age of 81 in Göttingen.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Hermann Weyl, one of his prominent students said the following words about him:-</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4">“No mathematician of equal stature has risen from our generation… Hilbert was singularly free from national and racial prejudices; in all public questions, be they political, social or spiritual, he stood forever on the side of freedom.”<em>— Hermann Weyl</em></p></blockquote></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
